3
00:00:15,020 --> 00:00:15,820
All right,

4
00:00:15,820 --> 00:00:20,180
let's get back to the subject at hand,

5
00:00:20,180 --> 00:00:21,360
which is classical mechanics.

6
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:22,380
No,

7
00:00:22,380 --> 00:00:23,460
classical field theory.

8
00:00:23,460 --> 00:00:27,440
But classical field theory,

9
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:29,220
as I've emphasized several times,

10
00:00:29,220 --> 00:00:31,340
is a special case of

11
00:00:31,340 --> 00:00:33,460
the general rules of classical mechanics.

12
00:00:34,420 --> 00:00:37,050
And that's the way it should

13
00:00:37,050 --> 00:00:39,680
be thought of as an example,

14
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:41,740
maybe the prime example,

15
00:00:41,740 --> 00:00:46,660
of the basic rules of classical mechanics.

16
00:00:49,660 --> 00:00:53,000
So I think we have to...

17
00:00:53,920 --> 00:00:57,170
review just a little bit about classical mechanics

18
00:00:57,170 --> 00:01:00,420
and then apply it in the field theory context.

19
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:04,830
What I particularly want to get to tonight

20
00:01:04,830 --> 00:01:08,780
is the connection between symmetries and conservation laws.

21
00:01:09,380 --> 00:01:09,880
Now,

22
00:01:09,880 --> 00:01:12,600
we've done that in the context of classical mechanics,

23
00:01:12,860 --> 00:01:16,190
but it's especially interesting and really

24
00:01:16,190 --> 00:01:19,520
takes a sort of front seat

25
00:01:20,280 --> 00:01:23,440
in the subject of relativistic mechanics.

26
00:01:23,460 --> 00:01:29,360
So let's go back a few steps

27
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:35,260
and review a little bit about classical mechanics.

28
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:37,820
Police action,

29
00:01:37,820 --> 00:01:38,880
Lagrangian,

30
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:42,680
and conservation laws in a simple context.

31
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:44,560
I don't think we'll have to do...

32
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:44,560
Hi,

33
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:45,420
come in.

34
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:48,940
I don't think we'll have to

35
00:01:48,940 --> 00:01:51,180
get too involved with Hamiltonian mechanics tonight,

36
00:01:51,919 --> 00:01:53,440
although later on we'll want to.

37
00:01:53,460 --> 00:01:56,640
But let's just review very quickly

38
00:01:56,640 --> 00:01:59,820
the mechanics of a system of particles.

39
00:02:00,679 --> 00:02:03,220
And for our purposes right now,

40
00:02:03,220 --> 00:02:06,960
we could have just one particle moving in one dimension,

41
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:10,430
although everything I say could be generalized just by

42
00:02:10,430 --> 00:02:13,680
putting a little index i next to some symbols.

43
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:14,680
I'll probably do that.

44
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:16,040
All right,

45
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:20,000
so we have a particle with a coordinate x.

46
00:02:22,040 --> 00:02:22,600
Incidentally,

47
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:23,440
sometimes it's a coordinate x.

48
00:02:23,460 --> 00:02:24,820
Sometimes I use q for coordinates.

49
00:02:24,860 --> 00:02:26,240
Sometimes I use x.

50
00:02:26,540 --> 00:02:29,900
I'll try to be clearer about the logic.

51
00:02:30,100 --> 00:02:32,460
If I change symbols,

52
00:02:32,460 --> 00:02:35,600
ask me about it if it confuses you,

53
00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:37,560
but I think probably it won't too much.

54
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:38,480
Anyway,

55
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:42,200
particle is described by a coordinate x,

56
00:02:42,200 --> 00:02:44,420
which depends on time.

57
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:45,720
Of course,

58
00:02:45,720 --> 00:02:46,940
there could be n particles,

59
00:02:46,940 --> 00:02:49,500
and they could have three-dimensional positions,

60
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:51,780
in which case we would just

61
00:02:51,780 --> 00:02:53,320
put a little i downstairs to indicate,

62
00:02:53,460 --> 00:02:54,920
which coordinate we were talking about.

63
00:02:55,940 --> 00:02:58,960
And the object of a problem of

64
00:02:58,960 --> 00:03:01,980
mechanics is to compute the orbit vertically.

65
00:03:02,180 --> 00:03:02,940
As always,

66
00:03:02,940 --> 00:03:03,720
we put time.

67
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:05,180
Horizontally,

68
00:03:05,180 --> 00:03:06,080
we put x.

69
00:03:07,280 --> 00:03:09,620
However many x coordinates we need,

70
00:03:09,620 --> 00:03:10,540
but I'll just draw one.

71
00:03:10,980 --> 00:03:13,570
And then the particle moves

72
00:03:13,570 --> 00:03:16,160
through spacetime along some orbit,

73
00:03:17,320 --> 00:03:19,260
according to the principle of least action.

74
00:03:19,900 --> 00:03:21,980
And the principle of least action says,

75
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:23,260
minimize...

76
00:03:23,460 --> 00:03:24,740
or at least make stationary.

77
00:03:25,260 --> 00:03:28,020
I'll describe what I mean by stationary in a minute.

78
00:03:28,340 --> 00:03:29,600
For our purposes,

79
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:30,360
it can mean minimize.

80
00:03:31,100 --> 00:03:32,280
Minimize the action,

81
00:03:32,280 --> 00:03:36,540
and the action is the integral of the Lagrangian,

82
00:03:36,620 --> 00:03:40,760
which depends on the coordinates and the velocities.

83
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:43,440
x dot stands for dx dt,

84
00:03:43,440 --> 00:03:45,980
integrated with respect to time.

85
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:50,400
And just to remind you,

86
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:53,340
we hold the endpoints fixed,

87
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:53,440
and we don't have to do anything else.

88
00:03:56,120 --> 00:04:00,060
And require that this quantity is minimized.

89
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:01,820
Minimized with respect to what?

90
00:04:01,940 --> 00:04:03,380
Whenever you say something is minimized,

91
00:04:03,460 --> 00:04:05,620
you imagine that you can

92
00:04:05,620 --> 00:04:07,780
explore some space of possibilities,

93
00:04:08,480 --> 00:04:12,500
and then minimizing means find the possibility

94
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:14,100
which gives you the minimum value

95
00:04:14,100 --> 00:04:15,700
of the action in this case.

96
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:19,740
So we're talking about exploring different trajectories.

97
00:04:21,339 --> 00:04:22,600
But in particular,

98
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:25,140
let's make a little change in the trajectory.

99
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,680
Some small change in the trajectory.

100
00:04:28,040 --> 00:04:30,100
The small change in the trajectory could

101
00:04:30,100 --> 00:04:32,160
involve a change from beginning to end,

102
00:04:32,260 --> 00:04:35,160
or it could just involve some small little region here

103
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:36,720
where the trajectory has changed.

104
00:04:38,620 --> 00:04:40,200
And recalculate the action.

105
00:04:42,700 --> 00:04:45,300
Recalculate the action as it deviates

106
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:47,900
from its value along the true trajectory,

107
00:04:48,180 --> 00:04:50,380
and then require that when we

108
00:04:50,380 --> 00:04:52,580
vary the trajectory a little bit,

109
00:04:52,580 --> 00:04:55,740
that the action always increases.

110
00:04:56,340 --> 00:04:56,860
Now,

111
00:04:56,860 --> 00:04:59,600
assuming that it increases

112
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:01,440
really is basically the same

113
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:03,280
as assuming that it doesn't change.

114
00:05:03,700 --> 00:05:04,700
Let me just remind you,

115
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:06,680
when you're minimizing a quantity,

116
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:07,340
for example,

117
00:05:07,340 --> 00:05:08,840
supposing you're minimizing something

118
00:05:08,840 --> 00:05:10,340
with respect to one variable,

119
00:05:10,640 --> 00:05:12,300
only one variable now.

120
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:13,900
In this context,

121
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:15,440
we're minimizing with respect to

122
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:16,980
an infinite number of variables.

123
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:19,550
The infinite number of variables are

124
00:05:19,550 --> 00:05:21,800
all the positions along the entire trajectory.

125
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:25,120
So it's a very complicated problem of minimization

126
00:05:25,740 --> 00:05:27,440
where we're minimizing with respect

127
00:05:27,440 --> 00:05:29,140
to an infinite number of variables.

128
00:05:29,700 --> 00:05:30,680
But nevertheless,

129
00:05:31,719 --> 00:05:33,859
let's examine the problem of minimizing

130
00:05:33,859 --> 00:05:36,000
something with respect to one variable first.

131
00:05:36,860 --> 00:05:37,460
All right,

132
00:05:37,460 --> 00:05:38,720
so the same quantity,

133
00:05:39,060 --> 00:05:40,020
in this case,

134
00:05:40,020 --> 00:05:41,120
let's just call it,

135
00:05:41,120 --> 00:05:42,940
let's call the quantity f,

136
00:05:43,160 --> 00:05:46,300
and it could be f of some variable x,

137
00:05:46,560 --> 00:05:49,620
and it's minimized at that point over here.

138
00:05:49,820 --> 00:05:51,060
So as you well know,

139
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:52,560
the rule for finding a minimum is,

140
00:05:52,580 --> 00:05:55,060
the minimum is just to differentiate x

141
00:05:58,260 --> 00:05:59,600
and set it equal to zero.

142
00:06:00,660 --> 00:06:02,500
Another way to say the same thing

143
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:05,760
is to require that at this point here,

144
00:06:05,900 --> 00:06:08,060
that if we make a little shift of x,

145
00:06:09,380 --> 00:06:10,880
a little shift of x,

146
00:06:11,080 --> 00:06:12,860
then that the change in f,

147
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:14,060
the change of f,

148
00:06:15,419 --> 00:06:16,200
delta f,

149
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:18,440
when we change x a little bit,

150
00:06:18,540 --> 00:06:19,740
should be zero.

151
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:25,100
That's the statement,

152
00:06:25,860 --> 00:06:27,080
that's the same as the

153
00:06:27,080 --> 00:06:28,300
statement that the derivative is zero,

154
00:06:28,760 --> 00:06:30,400
that the change is equal to zero.

155
00:06:30,860 --> 00:06:31,320
Okay?

156
00:06:31,540 --> 00:06:32,720
In both directions,

157
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:34,340
no matter which way you move.

158
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:36,620
If that's the case,

159
00:06:36,620 --> 00:06:37,620
that the change is zero,

160
00:06:38,940 --> 00:06:40,640
zero of course means only

161
00:06:40,640 --> 00:06:41,460
for very,

162
00:06:41,460 --> 00:06:42,920
very small excursions.

163
00:06:44,080 --> 00:06:44,680
All right?

164
00:06:44,740 --> 00:06:48,060
So the first order change should be equal to zero.

165
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:49,390
That's the same as saying df

166
00:06:49,390 --> 00:06:50,660
by dx is equal to zero.

167
00:06:52,719 --> 00:06:55,880
We could also say that the change in f

168
00:06:57,180 --> 00:06:59,060
when you move x a little bit

169
00:06:59,060 --> 00:07:01,920
is the derivative of f with respect to x

170
00:07:03,020 --> 00:07:04,080
times delta x.

171
00:07:07,280 --> 00:07:09,420
If df by dx is equal to zero,

172
00:07:09,520 --> 00:07:10,400
so is delta f.

173
00:07:10,560 --> 00:07:10,740
All right,

174
00:07:10,740 --> 00:07:11,380
so you get the idea.

175
00:07:11,820 --> 00:07:12,300
Now,

176
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:14,140
supposing you have many variables.

177
00:07:14,340 --> 00:07:14,980
In particular,

178
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:16,340
let's suppose we have two variables.

179
00:07:16,700 --> 00:07:18,090
So there's another variable sticking

180
00:07:18,090 --> 00:07:19,480
out of the blackboard here.

181
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:20,500
And again,

182
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:23,360
we have some function which now depends on two variables,

183
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:24,460
let's say x and y.

184
00:07:25,760 --> 00:07:27,540
And we're looking for some hole,

185
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:29,540
some dip in the function

186
00:07:29,540 --> 00:07:31,940
where it achieves its minimum

187
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:35,320
with respect to both variations in both directions.

188
00:07:36,340 --> 00:07:37,260
In fact,

189
00:07:37,260 --> 00:07:38,520
we're looking for a place where

190
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:40,720
no matter what direction we move off in,

191
00:07:42,860 --> 00:07:44,520
the function doesn't change

192
00:07:45,320 --> 00:07:46,480
to first order.

193
00:07:47,920 --> 00:07:48,440
That's,

194
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:50,360
the word for that is finding the stationary.

195
00:07:50,500 --> 00:07:51,400
The stationary points of the function.

196
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:52,860
But a particular example is

197
00:07:52,860 --> 00:07:54,180
finding the minimum of a function.

198
00:07:55,060 --> 00:07:57,040
If we found the minimum of a function

199
00:07:57,040 --> 00:07:59,800
with respect to all variations of this point,

200
00:08:00,540 --> 00:08:03,160
then what we want is that the derivative,

201
00:08:03,460 --> 00:08:05,520
that all the derivatives of f

202
00:08:05,520 --> 00:08:08,760
with respect to x equals zero,

203
00:08:08,860 --> 00:08:10,600
with respect to y equals zero.

204
00:08:13,340 --> 00:08:13,900
Or,

205
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:15,980
a shorthand version for it

206
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:18,300
is that if we're right at that point

207
00:08:18,300 --> 00:08:20,420
and we vary both x and y

208
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:21,900
or all of the variables,

209
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:23,100
whatever the variables are,

210
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:24,800
that the change in f,

211
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:25,880
again,

212
00:08:25,880 --> 00:08:26,520
should vanish.

213
00:08:26,980 --> 00:08:28,860
That's a shorthand version for saying that

214
00:08:28,860 --> 00:08:31,620
all the derivatives are equal to zero.

215
00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:37,480
So in the same manner,

216
00:08:38,280 --> 00:08:42,080
if we're looking for the minimum of the action,

217
00:08:43,159 --> 00:08:44,979
what we want to do is

218
00:08:44,979 --> 00:08:46,800
we want to explore nearby trajectories.

219
00:08:46,820 --> 00:08:47,860
We think we have a solution.

220
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:49,920
This is supposed to be a solution.

221
00:08:50,500 --> 00:08:51,600
We think we have a solution.

222
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:54,000
We want to explore nearby trajectories

223
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,980
and require that the change in the action is zero

224
00:08:58,350 --> 00:09:00,660
when we make a small change in trajectory.

225
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:05,520
Let's just write that the variation of

226
00:09:05,520 --> 00:09:08,820
L of x and x dot dt

227
00:09:10,300 --> 00:09:11,920
is equal to zero

228
00:09:12,500 --> 00:09:15,000
when we change the trajectory a little bit.

229
00:09:15,080 --> 00:09:15,180
Now,

230
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:17,300
what does changing the trajectory a little bit mean?

231
00:09:17,300 --> 00:09:20,380
It means we add to f to x of t,

232
00:09:20,640 --> 00:09:22,380
we add a small change.

233
00:09:22,900 --> 00:09:25,480
x of t was supposed to be the original solution.

234
00:09:26,760 --> 00:09:28,460
Let's add something small.

235
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:30,580
Let's call it epsilon

236
00:09:31,220 --> 00:09:33,620
times an arbitrary function of t.

237
00:09:36,940 --> 00:09:39,020
What are the variables in this problem

238
00:09:39,020 --> 00:09:41,020
that we're minimizing with respect to?

239
00:09:41,180 --> 00:09:43,160
We're minimizing with respect to

240
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:45,140
all these variables f of t,

241
00:09:45,180 --> 00:09:45,780
f of t1,

242
00:09:45,780 --> 00:09:46,540
f of t2,

243
00:09:46,540 --> 00:09:47,280
in fact,

244
00:09:47,300 --> 00:09:49,560
f all along here.

245
00:09:49,620 --> 00:09:51,500
This little bump here represents f.

246
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:55,600
So the question then is,

247
00:09:55,740 --> 00:09:57,760
how does the action change

248
00:09:58,300 --> 00:09:59,760
when we change x a little bit?

249
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:01,560
That's easy to work out.

250
00:10:01,940 --> 00:10:02,460
Incidentally,

251
00:10:02,460 --> 00:10:04,320
let's write this out.

252
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:07,020
The change in x is just

253
00:10:07,020 --> 00:10:09,480
equal to epsilon times f of t.

254
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:12,980
And of course,

255
00:10:12,980 --> 00:10:15,280
it also follows that the change in the velocity

256
00:10:16,040 --> 00:10:17,280
is epsilon times f of t.

257
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:22,420
We just differentiate with respect to time

258
00:10:22,420 --> 00:10:23,740
both sides of the equation.

259
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:26,440
If x changes by a little bit,

260
00:10:26,620 --> 00:10:30,380
then the velocity associated with x changes a little bit.

261
00:10:30,700 --> 00:10:33,660
And we can imagine we have any number of coordinates

262
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:34,880
and do the same thing.

263
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:36,680
It's not restricted to just one coordinate,

264
00:10:36,860 --> 00:10:38,900
but let's fix on x

265
00:10:38,900 --> 00:10:40,940
and see what this equation says.

266
00:10:41,380 --> 00:10:41,900
All right,

267
00:10:41,900 --> 00:10:43,160
so this is easy to work out.

268
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:45,330
We just write that this is

269
00:10:45,330 --> 00:10:47,260
that the change in the action

270
00:10:47,260 --> 00:10:52,160
is equal to the change in the Lagrangian

271
00:10:53,160 --> 00:10:55,060
integrated with respect to time.

272
00:10:55,280 --> 00:10:57,200
But what's the change in the Lagrangian

273
00:10:57,200 --> 00:10:59,120
if we change x and x dot a little bit?

274
00:10:59,560 --> 00:11:00,000
Well,

275
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:00,400
that's easy.

276
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:02,640
That's the derivative of the Lagrangian

277
00:11:05,240 --> 00:11:06,840
with respect to x

278
00:11:08,660 --> 00:11:09,980
times delta x.

279
00:11:10,420 --> 00:11:13,720
But delta x is just proportional to f of t.

280
00:11:13,860 --> 00:11:15,920
We can put an epsilon on the outside here.

281
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:20,720
The change of x is just f of t.

282
00:11:21,040 --> 00:11:22,940
So let's put f of t there.

283
00:11:24,020 --> 00:11:25,580
Epsilon times f of t,

284
00:11:25,580 --> 00:11:26,720
but I left the epsilon outside.

285
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:30,980
And then the Lagrangian also depends on the velocity.

