free to slide up and down,

2558
01:37:24,710 --> 01:37:27,550
then there's a symmetry which is the

2559
01:37:27,550 --> 01:37:30,390
symmetry of translation of the whole string.

2560
01:37:30,690 --> 01:37:32,050
Phi goes to phi plus a constant.

2561
01:37:32,490 --> 01:37:33,750
In that circumstance,

2562
01:37:33,750 --> 01:37:36,170
the integral of phi dot would be conserved.

2563
01:37:37,330 --> 01:37:38,510
And you know what the integral

2564
01:37:38,510 --> 01:37:39,690
of phi dot would be for this?

2565
01:37:39,950 --> 01:37:41,090
Remember what phi is.

2566
01:37:41,490 --> 01:37:43,510
It's just the vertical coordinate of the string.

2567
01:37:44,890 --> 01:37:47,080
It would just be the whole ordinary

2568
01:37:47,080 --> 01:37:49,270
momentum of the string moving up and down.

2569
01:37:50,390 --> 01:37:52,030
So if you give the whole thing a push up,

2570
01:37:52,030 --> 01:37:53,530
it will just continue to go up.

2571
01:37:54,630 --> 01:37:55,490
That's what it says.

2572
01:37:57,990 --> 01:37:59,480
So you have to be careful and

2573
01:37:59,480 --> 01:38:00,970
make sure that you really have the symmetry.

2574
01:38:01,930 --> 01:38:03,610
And you would not have the symmetry if

2575
01:38:03,610 --> 01:38:05,290
the ends of the string were pinned down.

2576
01:38:05,590 --> 01:38:07,240
But you do have the symmetry if the

2577
01:38:07,240 --> 01:38:08,890
ends of the string are free to move.

2578
01:38:09,390 --> 01:38:11,070
Do you know the term dip?

2579
01:38:11,070 --> 01:38:12,750
Do you know Dirichlet and Neumann boundary conditions?

2580
01:38:13,170 --> 01:38:13,670
Yeah,

2581
01:38:13,670 --> 01:38:13,910
okay.

2582
01:38:14,030 --> 01:38:16,790
So for Dirichlet boundary conditions,

2583
01:38:16,790 --> 01:38:18,470
that means the string pinned down.

2584
01:38:18,610 --> 01:38:19,690
You don't have the symmetry.

2585
01:38:19,990 --> 01:38:21,230
For Neumann conditions,

2586
01:38:21,230 --> 01:38:21,730
you do.

2587
01:38:22,330 --> 01:38:22,930
All right,

2588
01:38:22,930 --> 01:38:23,970
but this was just an example.

2589
01:38:25,550 --> 01:38:27,930
And it's not a terribly interesting symmetry.

2590
01:38:29,150 --> 01:38:30,150
In particular,

2591
01:38:30,150 --> 01:38:33,060
if we had the term in

2592
01:38:33,060 --> 01:38:35,970
the Lagrangian plus mu over 2.

2593
01:38:36,070 --> 01:38:37,930
There should be a one-half multiplying this.

2594
01:38:38,890 --> 01:38:40,430
Mu phi squared.

2595
01:38:41,810 --> 01:38:42,930
Minus mu phi squared.

2596
01:38:43,870 --> 01:38:46,920
Then we no longer have the symmetry because phi

2597
01:38:46,920 --> 01:38:49,970
squared will not be invariant when you shift phi.

2598
01:38:50,350 --> 01:38:51,550
If you shift phi,

2599
01:38:51,550 --> 01:38:53,590
phi squared is not invariant.

2600
01:38:53,630 --> 01:38:54,570
It changes.

2601
01:38:55,230 --> 01:38:57,510
So if we have this mu phi squared term,

2602
01:38:57,510 --> 01:38:59,010
we no longer have the symmetry.

2603
01:38:59,270 --> 01:39:00,710
So this is not a very robust symmetry.

2604
01:39:01,650 --> 01:39:03,600
It's just a particular case

2605
01:39:03,600 --> 01:39:05,550
which is very easy to illustrate.

2606
01:39:06,110 --> 01:39:07,890
Phi goes to phi plus a constant.

2607
01:39:07,890 --> 01:39:11,830
And as I said,

2608
01:39:11,830 --> 01:39:16,080
it corresponds to a sort of uniform center of mass

2609
01:39:16,080 --> 01:39:20,330
motion of the whole string vertically along the phi axis.

2610
01:39:24,190 --> 01:39:28,470
But an ordinary field in infinite space,

2611
01:39:28,470 --> 01:39:31,210
an ordinary field phi in infinite space,

2612
01:39:31,210 --> 01:39:33,490
if it doesn't have this mass term,

2613
01:39:33,490 --> 01:39:34,130
where is it?

2614
01:39:34,190 --> 01:39:35,440
If it doesn't have the term

2615
01:39:35,440 --> 01:39:36,690
that I call the mass term here.

2616
01:39:36,690 --> 01:39:39,810
Then it will also have a similar symmetry.

2617
01:39:40,570 --> 01:39:42,310
Phi goes to phi plus a constant.

2618
01:39:43,330 --> 01:39:43,870
Alright,

2619
01:39:43,870 --> 01:39:44,430
next time,

2620
01:39:44,430 --> 01:39:46,010
I think we're finished for today.

2621
01:39:46,610 --> 01:39:47,650
Next time,

2622
01:39:47,650 --> 01:39:50,710
we have to study spatial momentum.

2623
01:39:51,990 --> 01:39:52,890
Ordinary momentum.

2624
01:39:53,710 --> 01:39:55,910
The stuff that when it hits you,

2625
01:39:55,910 --> 01:39:57,070
knocks you on your...

2626
01:39:58,970 --> 01:40:00,290
Not field momentum,

2627
01:40:00,290 --> 01:40:02,535
but the kind of momentum that

2628
01:40:02,535 --> 01:40:04,780
really hits you when a pulse of...

2629
01:40:04,780 --> 01:40:07,700
When a high energy pulse of radiation hits you,

2630
01:40:07,700 --> 01:40:08,940
it gives you a push.

2631
01:40:09,400 --> 01:40:11,600
And that's a different kind

2632
01:40:11,600 --> 01:40:13,800
of momentum than this field momentum.

